==State and federal recognition== [[File:Tribal Territories Southern New England.png|thumb|Modern map showing linguistic groups, including areas where modern reservations are located]] At the end of 2009, the administration of President [[Barack Obama]] announced the [[Shinnecock Indian Nation]] had met the federal criteria for recognition as a tribe.<ref>{{Cite news|title=U.S. Eases Way to Recognition for Shinnecock |first=Danny |last=Hakim |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/16/nyregion/16tribe.html |newspaper=New York Times |date=2009-12-15 |accessdate=2009-12-17}}</ref> The Shinnecock were recognized by the United States government in October 2010 after a more than 30-year effort, which included suing the [[United States Department of the Interior|Department of Interior]].<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. Recognizes an Indian Tribe on Long Island, Clearing the Way for a Casino |first=Danny|last=Hakim |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/16/nyregion/16shinnecock.html?hp |newspaper=The New York Times |date=June 15, 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-15}}</ref> The Acting Principal Deputy Assistant Secretary of Indian Affairs, George T. Skibine, issued the final determination of the tribe's recognized status on June 13, 2010.<ref>Darling, Nedra. [http://www.bia.gov/idc/groups/public/documents/text/idc009847.pdf "Skibine Issues a Final Determination to Acknowledge the Shinnecock Indian Nation of Long Island, NY.] ''Office of the Assistant Secretary-Indian Affairs.'' 15 June 2010 (retrieved 12 July 2010)</ref>
New York State has recognized the Shinnecock, based at [[Shinnecock Reservation]] near [[Southampton]] and the Unkechaug. The latter's [[Poospatuck Reservation, New York|Poospatuck Reservation]] at [[Mastic, New York|Mastic]] is the smallest Indian reservation in the state. The Montaukett, Setalcott, and Matinnecock are all seeking both state and federal recognition.
