{{confused|Wynne}}
[[File:Wynee by John Meares2.jpg|thumb|Engraving of ''Wynee, a Native of Owyhee, one of the Sandwich Islands'' by a member of [[John Meares]]'s crew]]
[[File:Tianna by John Meares2.jpg|thumb|Engraving of ''Tianna, a Prince of Atooi'', who traveled with Wynee during the last leg of her journey home and was beside her at her death]]
'''Wynee''', also spelled '''Winee''' or '''Winée''' was the first [[Native Hawaiian]] from the [[Hawaiian Islands]] to travel abroad on a Western ship. She traveled to [[British Columbia]] and [[China]] before dying on the voyage home to Hawaii.{{sfn|Day|1984|page=8}}{{sfn|Ronck|1995|page=6}}

==Biography==
Wynee was originally from the island of [[Hawaii (island)|Hawaii]], known as ''Owyhee'' by European explorers at the time. In 1787, she became the first [[Native Hawaiian]] to sail abroad with a Western ship when she was hired as the servant or maid of [[Frances Barkley|Frances Hornsby Trevor Barkley]], the wife of Captain [[Charles William Barkley]], on the British ship ''[[Imperial Eagle (ship)|Imperial Eagle]]''. Barkley recorded her name as ''Wynee'' which was possibly an attempted spelling of ''[[wikt:wahine|wahine]]'', the [[Hawaiian language|Hawaiian]] word for woman.
She traveled to the [[Pacific Northwest]] and later to China.{{sfn|Day|1984|page=8}}{{sfn|Ronck|1995|page=6}}

The Barkleys intended to take her back to Europe but Wynee requested to return home and so she was left in the Portuguese colony of [[Macao]].{{sfn|Hill|Converse|2008|pages=40, 70–81}}
At [[Guangzhou|Canton]], she arranged to return to Hawaii aboard Captain [[John Meares]]'s ship '' Felice Adventurero'' with fellow Hawaiian "Tianna" ([[Kaiana]]), a member of the [[aliʻi]] (high chief) class from the island of [[Kauai]].{{sfn|Miller|1988|pages=5–6}} Traveling with them were two other Hawaiians: a stout man and a boy from [[Maui]] but they are not specifically named. She died of illness on the voyage home on February 5, 1788. Kaiana, who remained by her bedside caring for her, contracted a fever as well. He reportedly became seriously distraught upon learning of her death, although he would recover and arrive back home. Wynee bequeathed to him some trade articles she had acquired and asked him to deliver her remaining possessions to her father and mother; these items included mirrors, porcelain, Western clothing and other items she collected during her travel. She was buried at sea.{{sfn|Hill|Converse|2008|pages=40, 70–81}}{{sfn|Meares|1790|pages=9–10, 27–29}}{{sfn|Crossman|1991|page=37}}

Shortly after describing her last moments, Captain Meares wrote:
<blockquote>Thus died Winee, a native of Owhyhee, one of the Sandwich Islands, who possessed virtues that are seldom to be found in the class of her countrywomen to which she belonged, and a portion of understanding that was not be expected in a rude and uncultivated mind. It may not, perhaps, be uninteresting to mention the cause of this poor girl's departure from her friends and country, which it was her fate never to behold again.{{sfn|Meares|1790|pages=9–10, 27–29}}</blockquote>

